Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

By: Morris Muchiri Mugo¶

Introduction¶

Some of the questions to Investigate.¶

  1. What factors affect a loans outcome status?
  2. What affects the borrower APR or Interest Rate?
  3. Are there differences between Loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?
  4. Which Listing category had the highest and which had the lowest number of people taking Loans?
  5. How has the Borrower Rate been over the years?
  6. How has the numbers of Investors been over the years? ## Preliminary Wrangling

Quality Issues¶

  1. There are many rows where Proper score & Proper Rating are nulls
  2. The following variables are in using datatypes that won't be suitable for developing visuals Proper score, Open Revolving monthly payments, Total inquiries, Revolving credit Balance, Available Bank card credit, Total trades, Stated monthly income
  3. The following variables are in using datatypes that won't be suitable for developing visuals list category, Employment status, Is Borrower Home owner, Currently in a group

def plot_bar (a):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    prating_counts = df1[a].value_counts()
    prating_order = prating_counts.index
    sb.countplot(data=df1, x=a, color=base_color, order=prating_order)
    return plot_bar

# Plotting the distribution of Prosper Rating

p_list = df1['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].value_counts().sum()

plot_bar('ProsperRating (Alpha)');

# Recalculating the type_counts just to have clarity.
pr_counts = df1['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].value_counts()

# get the current tick locations and labels
locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=0) 

# loop through each pair of locations and labels
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
    count = pr_counts[label.get_text()]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/p_list)

    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
    plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'black')

# This function is used to change the count plot numbers into percentages
def without_hue(plot, feature):
    total = len(feature)
    for p in plot.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        plot.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 10, va='bottom', ha='center')

without_hue(ax, df1['ListingCategory (numeric)'])
plt.xlabel('listing category');

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • In ListCategories since most of the categories after ChargedOff the count was realy small I decided to put the percentages of the count in each categories to better visualize them
  • In the BorrowerRate Histogram I changed the xscale to log to better get the distribution and got a left skewed Histogram since before changing the log scale it was a bimodal distribution.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • In the Debt to Income Ratio, Stated Monthly Income and Monthly Loan Payment there were Outliers which I observed when I ploted their Histograms and removed them at the 99 percentile

# check the relationship between loan outcome status and the monthly loan payment
def violin_plot (a,b):
    plt.figure(figsize = [20,8])
    loan_counts = df1[a].value_counts()
    loan_order = loan_counts.index

    sb.violinplot(data=df1, x=a, y=b, color=base_color, inner='quartile',order=loan_order)
    plt.xticks(rotation=15)
    return violin_plot

violin_plot('LoanStatus','MonthlyLoanPayment');
